text:
#bellletstalk ğŸ’™
mental health has always been something i have struggled with for a large majority of my life. .
.
i finally found healing in sharing my story and i feel like iâ€™m finally at a place where i feel open enough to share it with you. and i hope my story inspires you to keep moving forward. .
.
trigger warning âš ï¸ âš ï¸ âŒâŒ
.
.
7 years ago i was raped, and i spent the past few years distracting myself by pushing my emotions down, pretending like that part of my life did not exist. i was ashamed, i was scared, i felt disgusted with myself. i became cold, i pushed people away, and i developed terrible trust issues.
.
.
my buried emotions manifested into anger, anxiety, isolation, suicidal thoughts, and insomnia. i would use the gym, school, work, business, success, money and even other peopleâ€™s problems, to distract myself from my own mind. .
.
after that event it was really difficult for me to love myself, and at times i still feel that way. i spent the last few years pulling away from my friendships, and relationships so i could focus on myself. heal myself, and love myself again. .
.
i had to reprogram my mind, my thoughts, and my beliefs about men. i had to learn how to forgive myself and let go of the past. i had to learn how to open my heart up to people who genuinely wanted to love  me. â¤ï¸
.
.
letting go of trauma is not easy, it takes time and consistent effort. if you ever feel like giving up please let this be a reminder that there is life after trauma and there are people in your life that love you. .
.
to be completely honest there is anxiety that is filling up in my body as i write this message to you all and  my brain is doing whatever it takes to stop me but my heart is telling me that there is at least one other woman or man who has experienced the same experience i have....this message is for you, i love you. â¤ï¸ #bellletstalk #endthestigma #mentalhealthawareness #metoo #trauma #love #depression #anxiety

"i guess that means he loves me right?" - an estimated 72% of females who commit suicide have experienced sexual or domestic abuse. the reason why people become suicidal are different, but abuse is a common denominator. if we want to see our suicide statistics change, we have to start by changing the things leading to it. 
full video premiering on facebook in 3 minutes! come and watch as we continue to remind our kids, teenagers and adults that abuse doesn't equal love. 
there is always hope.

text:
december 8, 2018 was the happiest & scariest  day of my life. many of you may ask, why? it should be the best day of your life? i too thought so. during my wedding planning i noticed that i was having frequent severe panic attacks, insomnia, hospital visits, paranoia, & negative suicide thoughts. my symptoms were manifesting worse & worse everyday. i kept asking myself, i love armand, why is all this happening? itâ€™s as if my mind was telling me no, but my heart was telling me yes. i followed through with what my heart was telling me. i married him & i was the happiest girl once we said i do. 
after our picture taking, my anxiety, filled my heart w/ full blown panic & it just hit me out of nowhere. i looked at my sister, as if i made the biggest mistake of my life. i knew that moment thereâ€™s something wrong with me. i couldnâ€™t chill & i couldnâ€™t breathe. at my reception, i was in complete panic although i did not show that i was in terror. looking around at everyone, people congratulating me, & feeling as if all this was too overwhelming. i wanted to run away. i woke up the next day looking at armand in fear & left crying! weâ€™ve been together for almost a decade, how is this possible?! i couldnâ€™t even enjoy the intimacy the night of. 
my friends & family, iâ€™ve been seeing a therapist & doctors and i am coming out of the closet. i have been educated that wedding stress had triggered a trauma response and am manifesting symptoms of c-ptsd (complex post traumatic stress disorder) due to *severe childhood trauma & abuse.
although this is a devastating time in my life as â€œa newly wedâ€, i see it as a blessing in disguise because i am now coming out to the world wanting to share my story & wanting to inspire others who have been affected by abuse. not only that, but to encourage women out there to never take shit from anyone. know your worth & fully love yourself first before you can love another person. there is happiness when youâ€™re in a dark place & you have to fight for it. as i am now fighting so hard for my happiness and for my faith. through therapy & through godâ€™s hands. this is our journey. this is my story. this is my recovery. #thebaclays #ptsd #cptsd #metoo

text:
i met armand in 2009. we met at cpk for a friendâ€™s birthday. we shook hands & took it as nothing. we definitely connected on a genuine level for the first few days of hanging out while he was in town though. i instantly felt i could trust this person. luckily he wanted to get coffee & i took the opportunity to spend time. it could be a sign of support since i never really spoke about my past life. it was to the point where i felt hopeless & lost. my feelings and secrets was such a burden. i just wanted to feel happy. maybe talking about it to someone else could help heal my broken heart. i was in a dark place. 
i told him my life story and who i was at 18 years old. at the time he was 23. he didnâ€™t judge me. he actually was concerned and asked me many things about abuse & what itâ€™s like. i told him it felt normal but it no longer happens but i carried it forever without being able to fully express who i am or who i was. i was misunderstood by a lot of people and it sucked. he told me, itâ€™s okay & i wonâ€™t ever tell your secrets. i accept you for who you are and we can continue to be friends if i ever needed someone to talk to. i felt gratified that i could share my life with someone who doesnâ€™t think itâ€™s â€œweirdâ€.
the day he left, i remember when we said bye. i hugged him and at that moment i felt instant connection that i couldnâ€™t explain. as if he was my soul mate. i kid you not. i didnâ€™t even have feelings for him. never even thought of it once.  we let go & thought to myself, â€œwoah that was somethingâ€. and once he left to go back to the bay, i felt lonely again more than ever. 
9 years later, iâ€™m 27 now, heâ€™s 33, weâ€™re married. crazy to say, i am still in a dark place. time is repeating itself because i never really recovered. only to realize that i was in denial. though i feel empty, i know i am thankful that you are now my husband & i have a second chance. | #thebaclays #chooseme #metoo #childhoodtrauma #ptsd #cptsd #iwantitbaclay

throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text: i have depression. i have struggled with ptsd most of my life. i have attempted suicide, multiple times. i have been sexually abused as a child. i have battled with thinking i didnâ€™t deserve to be a mother or wife or  live another day. i have been healed and torn open again and again. i have battled post pardum depression and been too ashamed to say so. i have lost many friends who havenâ€™t wanted to â€œput upâ€ with me. i have felt ostracized and ridiculed and looked at with judgment. i have almost lost my marriage, twice. i have battled chronic debilitating pain. i have made some really bad decisions. all while people onlook and say â€œbut you look (this way) or you have (that)â€ or â€œhow could you do that!?â€ no one knows the battles we face, the struggles we have endured or the sleepless nights or the fights in our mind. i have prayed in faith, asked for healing, prayed and fasted, taken every holistic recommendation, tried oils and diets etc, and i have taken western medication and given in to â€œbig pharmaâ€. i lay it all out there because ... this is my story, this is part of who i am. and i believe thru all the deep valleys and struggles god has a purpose and greater plan for these stories that donâ€™t define me but have brought me to where i am. i see now the deep need for empathy. because nothing has helped as much as the love and true friendship i have experienced from a select people and my heavenly father  who have seen me and been there for me thru such darkness. thru fire we forge strength and endurance, so we are complete lacking nothing. god is full of grace & ğŸ™ğŸ¼loving-kindness and i say with full confidence he is there in our darkest moments when we come face to face with him and we are met with gentle, peaceful... love. that he will always meet you where you are, even if thatâ€™s with nothing face down confused on the floor in snot and tears or feeling fearless with your hair blowing in the wind. he is there, and those that truly know him will be there for you also. i know for damn sure i will know how to be there for my sister, my friend, a stranger, a neighbor because i too know, that life is not perfect and neither are we... and we all just need some love.

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
a boy i once cared for told me that his friend got him piss-drunk and sexually assaulted him. the friend pretended like it never happened the next day.
my friend told her mom that her step-dad had touched her inappropriately. her mom promised it would never happen again. but it did. 
my mother told me that when she used to walk to school as a child, a teenage boy would follow her and flash her. she told my grandma, but grandma told her that these kinds of things happen to everyone. 
well, apparently she was right. the first time it happened to me, i was seven years old. the second time - sixteen. i knew that no matter who i told, it wouldnâ€™t matter. whatever i said would be brushed off. but i hoped- hoped so so badly- that someone would stand up for me or support me. but when i did open up about my experience, my loved ones asked me why i didnâ€™t throw a fist at his face. they asked me why i didnâ€™t run as far as my feet could carry me. and then, at the end of it all, they told me it was best that i forget what happened. 
at first, i told myself that what they said came from a place of love. i still donâ€™t question that. but i donâ€™t understand why the victims have to stay silent while the perpetrators sleep peacefully at night. why do the #survivors have to be triggered by the wrong word or touch while the abusers get to lead their lives unbothered? 
we need to change this. 
we have to change this. 
instead of teaching our loved ones to be quiet, we need to support them until theyâ€™ve gained the courage to break their silence and seek help.
so let my brothers and sisters speak their minds. let them not be ashamed of something they were not in control of. let them be the lotus flower that is born from the muck, that grows in the water and rises above it, unsoiled. 
#metoo

text:
"empowered women empower women"
///
oh wow, i didn't know that, just like when i thought women were fighting for similar rights just like men but now it has turned into only fighting for rights for the specifically. i don't know what happened, but things have been twisted and it just isn't about men, it isn't about "empowering" both of the sexes, it's about empowering them and they expect men to empower them because of their toxic dead brained mind to understand how egotistical that are & the arrogance that's flowing their actions and words. . . .
///
"triggered sexist men have arrived" 
yeah, they'll come because that's tired of exclusion and departure of them being thrown  under the rug because of your detrimental ideology that is only in support of women & how you degrade men's mentality, actions, and anything you can find about them to make them feel bad. and guess what, when you're fighting for your rights, and stepping all over people who are just trying to be them, the damage will already be done. there's no going back because you've already trampled on others for the things you want to achieve desperately; but in the wrong way.
///
"men don't need empowerment"
yeah, they do. you're just to stubborn and self absorbed in closure of your closed mindedness. you're only giving men/boys more and more reasons to leave and "walkway" from your misconceptions & dellusionary ideologies. no one's gonna be apart of that. and i don't support abusive and descriptively or verbal messages to be sent to others, i don't approve of that. but i don't approve of how this women's march has been doing. it's hateful, and i strongly disdain it.

text:
the 10th submission to the survivor tree project was perhaps the most difficult iâ€™ve worked on so far. you can see my anxiety manifesting in the leaf itself, if you look carefully: my hand shook as i transcribed this womanâ€™s powerful words. i had to stop and start several times, and the lines of cursive slipped and sloped as i lost myself in her story. â€¢
i pored over this submission for a myriad of reasons. 1. the survivor who submitted it is one of the most important people in my life. lee and i bonded as soon as we met in the summer of 2014; and since then, she has occupied a special place within me. the day she submitted her story was the day i started wondering if i could do her words any sort of justice. 2. because, of all the stories i have transcribed thus far, this one is the most similar to what i went through 13 months ago. itâ€™s still fresh. i still dream about it. i have always known that she and i are sisters in survivorship, but knowing that her experience echoed and emulated my nightmares so very closely left me feelingâ€¦ raw. powerless. depleted. i wept as though iâ€™d never stop because i felt like i knew her pain exactly as i know my own, and i didnâ€™t want that for her. â€¢
but the tears dried. i wiped my eyes, cleared my head, and transcribed her story. she is a warrior. she is an angel. i truly donâ€™t know where iâ€™d be without her. and she has not only helped me through her friendship: she has given herself to healing. she is the founder of survivor series- a community of survivors dedicated to encouraging and empowering the silenced. i was honored to be featured, and it was an amazing experience and significant step in my healing journey. one post is not enough to capture her story or her spirit or her strength, so iâ€™ll let her work speak for itself: check out @seenheardbelieved and click the bio link. she has helped so many. she is moving mountains. she is transforming surviving into thriving. âœ¨ğŸŒ± click the link in my bio if others would like to contribute their story to #thesurvivortreeproject. #survivor #survivoradvocate #believesurvivors #believewomen #believeblackwomen #rapesurvivor #metoo #timesup #endrapeculture #metoomovement #artist
name: Mel Hanley | Survivor Advocate

text:
pacific palisades
. 
marlonâ€™s hand rested in mine on my lap. we rode the the 10 from downtown until it ended in santa monica. it had been six hours since iâ€™d met him at his front door, four hours since dinner, two hours since iâ€™d decided i was going to kiss him. i let go of him when i saw the road flares ahead, and moved to two-and-ten. we drove past a motorcycle on its side, then the loose shattered quarter panel of a car. a highway patrolman waved us by as his partner flashed a light in the driversâ€™ eyes. there was no rider in sight - but also no white sheet or ambulance. i turned up the music on the radio.
. 
we stopped at the end of mt. holyoke, as close as we could get to the small park at the edge of the bluff, and walked past a sign that listed the park hours, sunrise to sunset, but neither of us gave it more than a glance. this wasnâ€™t young, cover-of darkness, reckless love. now, itâ€™s after three in the morning, and the moon, well the moon is there, too. a quick online search reveals that on february 28, 2016, the moon was waning gibbous. perhaps, like a lighthouse, itâ€™s a welcome on our arrival. perhaps, like a lighthouse, itâ€™s a warning that can be heeded only in retrospect - too late. . 
out in the cold winter pacific breeze, or maybe because of the accident, heâ€™s shivering. â€œwant my sweater?â€ itâ€™s not a question. not for the hundredth time but maybe thousandth time tonight, i smile, this time on seeing what he looks like in my clothes. when i wear that sweater now, itâ€™s our â€œfirst date sweater.â€
. 
weâ€™ve talked about what heâ€™s studying in grad school. his mom whoâ€™s a live-in caretaker. his sister whoâ€™s a voracious reader. his best friends who have no idea heâ€™s on a date with a guy. . 
weâ€™ve talked about the upcoming election and we donâ€™t talk much about our fathers because there isnâ€™t much to say - and that says plenty. . 
iâ€™ve told him that iâ€™m the oldest of four, but second of five if you count my best friend, and i do, who is now a brother to me. iâ€™ve told him about every single job iâ€™ve had and my small run ins with the law. iâ€™ve showed off by speaking in perfect spanish and french and portuguese. cont.

text:
toxic masculinity: yes, its personal.

i have a lot to say about the viral conversation that's happening right now about #toxicmasculinity. like, a lot.

i've realized that while i have been writing about my own healing coming out of a toxic #karmicrelationship, it really boils down to a story about my relationship with the toxic masculine. it's a relationship that goes way back.

this really is a conversation about all of us, as adults, being able to step up and heal ourselves and our relationship to our spiritual power, over egoic power, so that we can pass along that understanding and presence to our children.

toxic masculinity is learned, it is not innate. and we have the ability to learn it young, if we are wounded early enough. which, sadly, most of us were.

i was only in elementary school when i was teased for being too "girly." i remember being bullied for being excited to learn about my body in biology class, excited and amazed by the fact that the female body is designed to create and birth life. like, wow, that is some serious spiritual power, and i wanted to know all about it.

but someone else had been wounded, they knew the mind of the toxic masculine, they lashed out at me, and it cut me deep. (i'm still healing from this one actually.) over the years, i'd experience more teasing, most of it directed at the more feminine traits i expressed. my passion, idealism, intuition, vision, creativity, sensitivity and empathy. all were fair game to attack.

what i've learned through my adult experience of serial relationships with toxic masculinity is that it is not relegated only to males, and it hurts everyone.

i've learned that at its core, this mentality has an energy of wanting to attack, break down, destroy, and suppress the feminine. what i understand is that this comes from a deep seated fear.

there's a fear that is the driving force behind the mentality of being unable to acknowledge or accept the feminine within, or in a form outside of self.

let me make this clear: i am not talking men vs women here. this is about the yin and yang elements of the energy of all life.

i was only in elementary school when i was teased for being too "girly." i remember being bullied for being excited to learn about my body in biology class, excited and amazed by the fact that the female body is designed to create and birth life. like, wow, that is some serious spiritual power, and i wanted to know all about it.

but someone else had been wounded, they knew the mind of the toxic masculine, they lashed out at me, and it cut me deep. (i am still healing from this one actually.) over the years, i'd experience more teasing, most of it directed at the more feminine traits i expressed. my passion, idealism, intuition, vision, creativity, sensitivity and empathy. all were fair game to attack.

what i have learned through my adult experience of serial relationships with toxic masculinity is that it is not relegated only to males, and it hurts everyone.

i have learned that at its core, this mentality has an energy of wanting to attack, break down, destroy, and suppress the feminine. what i understand is that this comes from a deep seated fear.

there's a fear that is the driving force behind the mentality of being unable to acknowledge or accept the feminine within, or in a form outside of self.

let me make this clear: i am not talking men vs women here. this is about the yin and yang elements of the energy of all life.

text:
1970 ... that means iâ€™m 49. for real how did that happen and why is this my #midlifecrisis? i actually think iâ€™m clocking in a second midlife crisis here. 
in a haze and whirl of too many parties and drugs wrapped in a great big blanket of #metoo i ran away from nc to start a new world in #seattle. i am now a multicolored hair aging #hipster on #capitolhill in seattle that had quite an amazing ride working for #microsoft for 5 years before a contract was yanked out from under me (promise a post on that later). that running away and starting a #newlife was a benchmark of some type of midlife crisis ... iâ€™ve seen and heard other tales of people chucking their lives to the winds and heading for something new and different. i do not look back - nor do i regret!

now iâ€™m in school at seattle central college #scc in web development. i love what i am studying but the stress of living a 20 year old existence in an almost 50 year old body can be intense af! 
but once again i am not alone. this is the newest level of midlife crisis for #genx. we donâ€™t get fancy sports cars we get to go back to school. genx is right smack in the middle of aging and burgeoning technologies and we have to pay the price to learn the new stuff while defending the old stuff. hardly anyone cares about my #excel skills itâ€™s more a case of â€œwhy donâ€™t you know #sql already?â€ old school â€œkeep to yourself and create your ownâ€ workspace has been replaced by #pairprograming and the age of #github and shared #repositories. in the #it world staying vital means staying up on the latest and greatest. with #genx we are still holding onto an expectation that life comes with one job you work until you get your #goldpocketwatch and the job cares about you and sponsors your development. that is not the case in the millennial marketplace. if you arenâ€™t teaching yourself no one cares if you are left behind. some of us out there got that message sooner than others. if that message came through i didnâ€™t get it. i get it now! 
although school is an epic struggle of finances and #packagedramen it is worth the struggle. i have to believe and have faith that it is.

text:
setelah kasus kekerasan seksual yang dialami seorang mahasiswi bernama agni di ugm diekspos oleh pers mahasiswa setempat, balairung press, ada peledakan pembahasan tentang kekerasan seksual di kampus universitas di seluruh indonesia. tetapi kasus agni bukan kasus kekerasan seksual pertama yang terjadi di kampus, dan tentu bukan kasus terakhir. sayang sekali, banyak korban belum pernah mendapatkan keadilan dan malah diremehkan, dirundung, diintimidasi, dan dikeluarkan universitas.
mengapa kekerasan seksual sering terjadi di kampus universitas, dan dilakukan baik mahasiswa maupun dosen? apakah gerakan #metoo yang sudah sangat mengubah perilaku dan cara berpikir di negara lain bisa berhasil di indonesia juga? dan bagaimana kita bisa membantu menghilangkan kekerasan seksual di kampus?

jakarta feminist discussion group (jfdg) dan yayasan pantau menyelenggarakan 'diskusi kekerasan seksual dan gerakan #metoo di kampus' sebagai bagian dari rangkaian pra-acara women's march jakarta pada sabtu, 9 februari 2019 pukul 9.30 s.d. 13.00 wib di ruang komunal (facebook), one pacific place, senayan.

dimoderatori febriana firdaus (wartawan, jakarta), diskusi ini dihadiri pembicara
1. citra maudy (editor, balairung press, universitas gadjah mada, yogyakarta)
2. evi mariani (editor, the jakarta post, jakarta)
3. saras dewi (dosen, universitas indonesia, depok)

registrasi bisa dilakukan di formulir berikut. tempat terbatas!

http://bit.ly/metookampuswmj2019

#womensmarchjkt #beranibersuara #metoo #hearmetoo #akujuga

info ke @womensmarchjkt dan @febrofirdaus

there are things that remain
i long to release 
but every time i stir them up in my mind
words refuse to exit my mouth 
if i allow my consciousness to descend 
into the cavern where those truths reside
stepping down each rung with a caution
a weightlessness i grew accustomed to
sacrificing my voice 
ensuring the darkness i hid in 
remained in tact
landmines buried to keep me in line 
you joked youâ€™d never hit me
because i was bigger than you
the way youâ€™d be certain to say with a smile
â€œi want to shake youâ€
â€œi left so i wouldnâ€™t hit youâ€
as though i should be grateful 
for such restraint 
you never laid your hands on me 
at least not in the daylight 
not in the ways that one could point to
when nothing felt right 
your words beat me instead 
battered down
bloody 
cement poured down my throat
setting in my every joint
making it easier each time to ignore
my words
calling me a tease
when all i did was breathe
existing each moment
cautious with every movement so 
as to not unintentionally entice 
shut myself in that tiny bathroom
pieces of me falling off
sobbing in silence 
aching
bleeding 
while 20 feet away you rested peacefully 
are you even aware of what you did to me?
all this time later
i still canâ€™t call it what it was

a piece of me still sits in that darkness
hidden away for fear of what those i 
love will say 
the day that shadow i left inside
breaks away 
aches too deeply for the light 
to stay left behind

update, 18.30 wib, 31 jan: kuota sudah penuh.  terima kasih atas ketertarikannya. nanti akan ada facebook live juga.

setelah kasus kekerasan seksual yang dialami seorang mahasiswi bernama agni di ugm diekspos oleh pers mahasiswa setempat, balairung press, ada peledakan pembahasan tentang kekerasan seksual di kampus universitas di seluruh indonesia.

tetapi kasus agni bukan kasus kekerasan seksual pertama yang terjadi di kampus, dan tentu bukan kasus terakhir. sayang sekali, banyak korban belum pernah mendapatkan keadilan dan malah diremehkan, dirundung, diintimidasi, dan dikeluarkan universitas.

mengapa kekerasan seksual sering terjadi di kampus universitas, dan dilakukan baik mahasiswa maupun dosen? apakah gerakan #metoo yang sudah sangat mengubah perilaku dan cara berpikir di negara lain bisa berhasil di indonesia juga? dan bagaimana kita bisa membantu menghilangkan kekerasan seksual di kampus?

jakarta feminist discussion group (jfdg) dan yayasan pantau menyelenggarakan 'diskusi kekerasan seksual dan gerakan #metoo di kampus' sebagai bagian dari rangkaian pra-acara women's march jakarta pada sabtu, 9 februari 2019 pukul 9.30 s.d. 13.00 wib di ruang komunal (facebook), one pacific place, senayan.

dimoderatori febriana firdaus (wartawan, jakarta), diskusi ini dihadiri pembicara
1. citra maudy (reporter, balairung press, universitas gadjah mada, yogyakarta)
2. evi mariani (editor, the jakarta post, jakarta)
3. saras dewi (dosen, universitas indonesia, depok)

sekalian ada ada penyerahan oktovianus pogau award kepada citra dan thovan dari balairung press @bppmbalairung yogyakarta untuk keberanian dalam jurnalisme. selengkapnya ada di http://pantau.or.id/?/=d/789 
registrasi bisa dilakukan di formulir berikut. tempat terbatas!

tetapi kasus agni bukan kasus kekerasan seksual pertama yang terjadi di kampus, dan tentu bukan kasus terakhir. sayang sekali, banyak korban belum pernah mendapatkan keadilan dan malah diremehkan, dirundung, diintimidasi, dan dikeluarkan universitas.

mengapa kekerasan seksual sering terjadi di kampus universitas, dan dilakukan baik mahasiswa maupun dosen? apakah gerakan #metoo yang sudah sangat mengubah perilaku dan cara berpikir di negara lain bisa berhasil di indonesia juga? dan bagaimana kita bisa membantu menghilangkan kekerasan seksual di kampus?

jakarta feminist discussion group (jfdg) dan yayasan pantau menyelenggarakan 'diskusi kekerasan seksual dan gerakan #metoo di kampus' sebagai bagian dari rangkaian pra-acara women's march jakarta pada sabtu, 9 februari 2019 pukul 9.30 s.d. 13.00 wib di ruang komunal (facebook), one pacific place, senayan.

text: last weekend i spoke to a room full of sexual assault survivors. i could see the scars on their hearts and heard the stories of their healing. some of that healing had only been introduced 5 minutes prior. thereâ€™s an idea about sexual assault that it only is valid if it was violent. many times it is, but sometimes itâ€™s an ignored series of â€œno.â€ that is just as valid. if you or anyone you know has stayed silent because their lack of consent was ignored, that doesnâ€™t make it okay. sexual assault is like a plague on college campuses and as i watched the latest episode of the bachelor my heart sank listening to @caelynnmillerkeyes talk about her very traumatic (& more violent than mine) experience. i have to publicly acknowledge her bravery here because this topic is something iâ€™ll never stop fighting for and it was so empowering to hear her speak up. if you have been sexually assaulted and have been struggling with ptsd, please tell someone that is a safe person. we have resources at @unveiledcampaign for you online and i personally wonâ€™t stop fighting for us. if you want to raise awareness at your college on this topic, please reach out so i can join you in the war, on the ground.

text:
unfortunately this was a scene that was a norm in my home when i was married to my ex. i remember feeling on edge most of the time, never knowing what mood or state of mind he would be in. living on egg shells because his anger was always bubbling under the surface, and i never knew when he would explode.

gosh, living like that for years really messed with my head. the name calling, manipulation, control, gaslighting, emotional/mental/physical abuse, and isolation made my life fearful and miserable.

thank god i'm free from that life...emotionally, physically, spiritually and mentally free. it's taken years and hard work to detox myself from this shit. but worth it.

if the above pic is a "norm" in your relationship and/or home, please know it's not normal...took me years to realize this truth. know that abuse escalates and slowly gets worse. and that there is help, and life can be much better than what you may be experiencing.

to my fellow dv survivors, i know many of you can relate to what i'm ğŸ˜Š saying. freedom feels good doesnt it?

still a queen ğŸ‘‘âœŠ.
.

.
